commit.message: Add a note on compiler requirements

Stop forcing target flags globally while building

Remove the code appending options needed for hardware CRC32c
implementations globally.  This is incorrect, as it permits the compiler
to emit target-specific code (i.e. SSE4.2 code or ARMv8 code) on systems
where the processor does not actually support them.

This logic has been replaced by inline use of target-specific attributes
and pragmas in the individual files.  They should work reliably on x86
targets and on the majority of ARM64 targets.

Fixes #30

Use `#pragma GCC target` to enable CRC in ARM64 hw implementation

Use `#pragma GCC target ("+crc+crypto")` to enable the necessary
features in the ARM64 hardware CRC32c implementation.  This makes
it possible to build it without setting `-march` globally.  This should
work with GCC 6.3+, and Clang 18 (tested via godbolt.org).  Older
versions of Clang may require explicit `-march=` still.

Use `__attribute__ ((target("crc32")))` for hw CRC32c function

Mark the x86 hardware CRC32c function with `__attribute__
((target("crc32")))` on GCC and compatible compilers.  This makes it
possible to compile the project without explicit `-msse4.2`.
This should work with GCC 4.9.0+ and Clang 3.8+ (roughly confirmed
via godbolt.org).

commit.message:
Add clarity to test outputs

At the moment we can't clearly evaluate (but can guess) whether hardware
support has been found or not just by looking at the tests results for
"auto". I've thus added an additional printing of the "hardware_based"
property of the crc32c module to each test output.

Additionally the test output was overall a bit difficult to read,
without a clear separation between the two runs for "auto" and "force".
This has been improved by adding a banner at the beginning of each run
showing the mode under test.

Signed-off-by: Rodrigo Tobar <rtobar@icrar.org>

commit.message:
Define IS_INTEL/ARM based on compiler macros

This allows macOS universal builds, which in the case of Python
Extensions is implemented by compiling single files against different
architectures in a single pass and into a single output file (using
"-arch x86_64 -arch arm"). Each architecture "slice" results in the
compilation of the sources with a different set of macro definitions,
and therefore we need to define these macros at the source code level
rather than setting them externally.

Signed-off-by: Rodrigo Tobar <rtobar@icrar.org>
